properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter weather conditions are expected over parts of southern Alberta starting this evening. Reduced visibility in blowing snow and heavy falling snow is expected to last through Saturday for some areas. There is some uncertainty as to how far south this storm system will develop; certainty will increase as the event draws nearer and this watch may be upgraded to a warning. Unseasonably cold temperatures will settle in over the province beginning Friday. Temperatures are expected to remain much colder than normal until early next week. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and strong southeasterly winds expected on Friday night. Total rainfall: 15 to 25 mm. Locally higher amounts possible. Maximum wind gusts: 80 km/h and possibly higher, with gusts to 130 km/h likely from Margaree Harbour to Bay St. Lawrence. Locations: Cape Breton Island. Time span: Friday evening into early Saturday morning. Remarks: A mix of freezing rain, snow, and rain is expected to begin Friday evening over Cape Breton Island, changing to rain late in the evening and becoming heavy at times with strong southeasterly winds. The rain will taper to showers of flurries early Saturday morning as winds diminish and shift to westerly. Fairly strong westerly winds and flurries will continue through much of the weekend. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, blowing snow and strong winds to end the week. An intense low pressure system will affect the whole province Friday and Saturday. An important snowfall will leave significant amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres of snow. Strong to high winds combined with snow will greatly reduce visibilities in blowing snow over the most exposed areas. The Quebec City area poses a challenge as localities north of the St. Lawrence may receive significant amounts of snow and ice pellets while also being affected by a more or less extended period of freezing rain. Areas south of the St. Lawrence River could be affected by some snow, freezing rain and even rain. As the exact track of the low remains uncertain, the type and amount of precipitation received could be significantly affected. Consider modifying any non-essential travel plans. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
